---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-venezuela', text: 'Leaving Venezuelan Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'currency-matters', text: 'Currency Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Latin America Insurance', href: '/best/latin-america-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Spanish Expat Insurance', href: '/best/spanish-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'spanishSupport', header: 'Spanish Support' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'latamNetwork', header: 'LATAM Network' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', spanishSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Strong', latamNetwork: 'Strong', price: '$175/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', spanishSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Excellent', latamNetwork: 'Good', price: '$195/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', spanishSupport: 'Yes', usNetwork: 'Good', latamNetwork: 'Good', price: '$170/mo' },
  { provider: 'April International', spanishSupport: 'Full', usNetwork: 'Good', latamNetwork: 'Strong', price: '$160/mo' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', spanishSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Excellent', latamNetwork: 'Good', price: '$180/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Venezuelan Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Venezuelan expats. Find USD-denominated coverage for the US, Spain, Colombia, and other destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Venezuelan Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Venezuela's diaspora has grown dramatically. Here's how to stay protected with USD-denominated coverage wherever you've relocated."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/venezuelan-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Venezuelan expats have relocated across the Americas, Europe, and beyond. USD-denominated coverage is essential given Venezuela's currency situation. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Venezuelan expats. Full Spanish support, strong US and Latin American networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Spanish support available.</li>
    <li><strong>April International:</strong> French insurer with excellent Spanish support. Strong Latin American presence.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices.</li>
    <li><strong>GeoBlue:</strong> Strong US networks for those in the United States.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="USD Coverage Essential"
    description="Venezuelan bolívar hyperinflation makes USD-denominated coverage critical. Your policy limits maintain real value. This isn't optional—it's essential for actual protection."
    buttonText="Get USD Coverage Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-venezuela">Leaving Venezuelan Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Venezuela's healthcare system has faced severe challenges. Here's the situation:
  </p>

  <h3>Public Healthcare Crisis</h3>
  <p>
    Venezuelan public healthcare has been severely impacted by the economic crisis. Medicine shortages, equipment failures, and staff departures have degraded services. Many Venezuelans seeking healthcare travel abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>IVSS (Social Security)</h3>
  <p>
    The Venezuelan social security system (IVSS) provides healthcare to contributing workers. Coverage is limited to Venezuela and the system has faced funding challenges.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Venezuelan Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private health insurance in bolívares has lost value due to hyperinflation. Dollar-denominated policies from Venezuelan insurers are limited. International insurance provides stable coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>No International Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    Venezuelan healthcare systems provide no meaningful international coverage. Venezuelans abroad need fully independent international insurance.
  </p>

  <h2 id="currency-matters">Currency Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Currency is the critical consideration for Venezuelan expats:
  </p>

  <h3>Hyperinflation Impact</h3>
  <p>
    Venezuelan bolívar hyperinflation has made local currency coverage worthless. Any bolívar-denominated insurance has effectively no value. USD coverage is the only practical option.
  </p>

  <h3>USD-Denominated Benefits</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage limits maintain actual purchasing power</li>
    <li>Claims paid at real international costs</li>
    <li>Premiums stable in hard currency</li>
    <li>Complete protection against currency collapse</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Payment Options</h3>
  <p>
    Most Venezuelan expats pay from foreign income or savings:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>International credit cards</li>
    <li>Wire transfers from foreign accounts</li>
    <li>Payment from destination country income</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Spanish Language Support</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Full Spanish-language support matters during medical emergencies. Cigna and April International offer excellent Spanish service throughout their operations.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive USD-denominated coverage with full Spanish support. Strong networks in the US (Florida, Texas especially) and throughout Latin America. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    24/7 Spanish service for support and claims. Venezuela coverage can be added but healthcare access there is limited.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Venezuelan expats who want reliable global coverage with native Spanish support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent US networks. Spanish support is available. Service quality is outstanding with comprehensive benefits.
  </p>

  <p>
    Higher pricing reflects premium quality. Best for those who can afford the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Venezuelan professionals who want top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>April International</h3>
  <p>
    April International is a French insurer with excellent Spanish support and strong Latin American presence. Good networks in Spain and the Americas. Competitive pricing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Popular among Latin American expats globally.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Venezuelan expats in Spain or Latin America who want full Spanish service.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers good global coverage at competitive prices. Spanish support available. Strong networks in Europe and adequate coverage elsewhere.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Venezuelan expats seeking good value, especially for European destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>GeoBlue</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue offers strong US coverage, particularly valuable for Venezuelan expats in Florida and other US destinations. US network is excellent. Latin American coverage is adequate.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Venezuelan expats in the US who prioritize strong US networks.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get USD-denominated quotes from multiple providers. Prioritize Spanish support and strong networks in your destination region."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Venezuelan diaspora is spread across many countries:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    Large Venezuelan community, especially in Florida (Miami, Doral, Weston). US healthcare is extremely expensive—comprehensive coverage is essential. Many Venezuelan doctors practice in South Florida.
  </p>

  <h3>Colombia</h3>
  <p>
    Neighboring country with large Venezuelan population. Colombian healthcare is accessible and affordable. International insurance provides access to quality private facilities.
  </p>

  <h3>Spain</h3>
  <p>
    Historical and linguistic ties make Spain popular. Spanish healthcare covers legal residents. Private insurance supplements public coverage. Madrid has a significant Venezuelan community.
  </p>

  <h3>Chile</h3>
  <p>
    Significant Venezuelan community. Chilean healthcare requires private insurance (ISAPRE) or public coverage (FONASA). International insurance provides coverage during immigration process.
  </p>

  <h3>Peru and Ecuador</h3>
  <p>
    Large Venezuelan populations in both countries. Healthcare systems vary—international insurance ensures access to quality facilities.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Venezuelan insurance valid?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Venezuelan bolívar-denominated insurance has effectively no value due to hyperinflation. USD-denominated international insurance is required for real coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">How do I pay for international insurance?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Venezuelan expats pay from foreign income using international credit cards or wire transfers from non-Venezuelan bank accounts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I get coverage for Venezuela visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Given healthcare challenges in Venezuela, international coverage with evacuation benefits may be more useful than local coverage. Consider your specific needs.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about medical evacuation?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Evacuation coverage is important, especially if visiting Venezuela or living in countries with limited healthcare. All recommended insurers include evacuation benefits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Spanish support important?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes. Native Spanish support reduces stress during medical emergencies. Cigna and April International offer excellent Spanish service.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Venezuelan doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, many Venezuelan doctors have emigrated—especially to Miami, Spain, and other Latin American countries. Community networks can help find familiar providers.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Venezuelan expats need USD-denominated international insurance—Venezuelan coverage is worthless due to currency collapse. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for full Spanish support and strong regional networks.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford the best. <strong>April International</strong> is excellent for Spain and Latin America. <strong>GeoBlue</strong> suits those prioritizing US coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't attempt to rely on any bolívar-denominated coverage—it has no real value. USD-denominated international insurance is the only practical option.
  </p>

</PageShell>
